        <name>1.4.1.13 Simplifying simple algebraic fractions</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Leave the expression in its most simplified form&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts_inline"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;\(\dfrac{{@a1@}x}{x}\)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;\(\dfrac{{@a2@}x}{x^2}\)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;\(\dfrac{{@a1@}s}{s^{@a3@}}\)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;\(\dfrac{{@a4@}z^{{@a1@}}}{{@a5@}z^2}\)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When simplifying remember only common factors can be cancelled.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4 class="HELM_solution"&gt;Solution&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;[[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In the expression \(\dfrac{{@a1@}x}{x}\), the term \(x\) is common to both the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(\dfrac{{@a1@}x}{x} = \displaystyle{{@ta1@}}.\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In the expression \(\dfrac{{@a2@}x}{x^2}\), the term \(x\) is common to both the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(\dfrac{{@a2@}x}{x^2} = \dfrac{{@a2@} \times x}{x \times x} = \displaystyle{{@ta2@}}.\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The expression \(\dfrac{{@a1@}s}{s^{@a3@}}\) has the common factor \(s\) in both the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(\dfrac{{@a1@}s}{s^{@a3@}} = \dfrac{{@a1@} \times s}{s \times s^{@a6@}} = \displaystyle{{@ta3@}}.\)
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In the expression \(\dfrac{{@a4@}z^{{@a1@}}}{{@a5@}z^2}\), \(z\) and \({@a5@}\) are both common to the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(\dfrac{{@a4@}z^{{@a1@}}}{{@a5@}z^2} = \dfrac{{@a5@} \times 3 \times z^2 \times z^{{@a7@}}}{{@a5@} \times z^2} = \displaystyle{{@ta4@}}.\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
